n                <origination label=\"Creator\" encodinganalog=\"245$c\">\n                  <corpname encodinganalog=\"110\" normal=\"Alpha 66 (Organization)\" source=\"lcnaf\" role=\"Collector\">Alpha 66 (Organization)</corpname>\n                  <persname encodinganalog=\"100\" normal=\"Nazario SargÃ©n, AndrÃ©s\" source=\"local\" role=\"Collector\">Nazario SargÃ©n, AndrÃ©s, 1916-2004</persname>\n                </origination>\n                <physdesc label=\"Physical Description\">\n                  <extent encodinganalog=\"300\" type=\"Boxes\">29.00</extent>\n                </physdesc>\n                <physdesc label=\"Alternate Extent Statement\" encodinganalog=\"300$a\">13 linear feet</physdesc>\n                <langmaterial encodinganalog=\"546\" label=\"Language of Materials\">\n                  <language encodinganalog=\"041\" langcode=\"spa\">Spanish;Castilian</language>\n                </langmaterial>\n                <repository encodinganalog=\"852$b\" label=\"Repository\">\n                  <corpname>University of Miami Cuban Heritage Collection</corpname>\n                  <address>\n                    <addressline>University of Miami Libraries</addressline>\n                    <addressline>1300 Memorial Drive</addressline>\n                    <addressline>Coral Gables, FL, </addressline>\n                    <addressline>URL: http://library.miami.edu/chc/</addressline>\n                    <addressline>Email: chc@miami.edu</addressline>\n                    <addressline>Phone: (305) 284-4900</addressline>\n                    <addressline>Fax: (305) 284-4901</addressline>\n                  </address>\n                </repository>\n                <note encodinganalog=\"500\" label=\"Note\">\n                  <p>Other Information:</p>\n                  <p>This collection was processed with the support of the Miami-Dade County Department of Cultural Affairs and the Cultural Affairs Council, the Miami-Dade County Mayor and Board of County Commissioners.</p>\n                  <p>Additional information may be found at http://proust.library.miami.edu/findingaids/legacy/chc5157CL.pdf</p>\n                </note>\n              </did>\n              <!--COLLECTION LEVEL METADATA: -->\n              <bioghist altrender=\"Historical Note\" encodinganalog=\"545\">\n                <head>Historical Note:</head>\n                <p>The Cuban exile paramilitary organization known as Alpha 66 was first organized and founded in Puerto Rico in 1961 with 66 men. The group was created with the intention of maintaining the fighting spirit of the Cuban people after the Bay of Pigs Invasion. General Secretary AndrÃ©s Nazario SargÃ©n was a founder of Alpha 66 along with other prominent anti-communist fighters such as his older brother Aurelio Nazario, Eloy GutiÃ©rrez Menoyo and Antonio Veciana.</p>\n                <p>Other organizations joined this armed struggle against Cuban communism, and thus began the first movements and incursions into the Cuban coast.  In 1962, the Second Escambray Front (<emph render=\"italic\">Segundo Frente del Escambray</emph> â€“ SFE) and Alpha 66 became one, with Veciana as a coordinator and GutiÃ©rrez Menoyo in charge of the military training. Later, Alpha 66 joined forces with the Revolutionary Movement of the People (<emph render=\"italic\">Movimiento Revolucionario del Pueblo â€“ </emph>MRP) in the Revolutionary Alliance (<emph render=\"italic\">Alianza Revolucionaria</emph>).</p>\n                <p>In 1964, the Revolutionary Alliance executed â€œPlan Omegaâ€ that involved situating a well-equipped guerrilla force inside Cuba.  Delegations from California, Florida, New York, Puerto Rico and Venezuela assembled a War Council carrying out propaganda and finance operations with the slogan, â€œ<emph render=\"italic\">El Plan Omega estÃ¡ en marcha</emph>â€ (â€œThe Omega Plan is in motionâ€). The central goal was to overthrow the Castro regime in Cuba.</p>\n                <p>â€œEl Plan Omegaâ€ failed, and Ernesto DÃ­az, Pedro RodrÃ­guez, and Eloy GutiÃ©rrez Menoyo, were captured along with three other Alpha officers: Domingo Ortega, RamÃ³n Quesada GÃ³mez, and Noel Salas Santos. After their capture, broadcast and propaganda campaigns were launched to gain release for these political prisoners. Their failure and imprisonment affected many of the rebel groups in Cuba and the Cuban exile community as a whole.  The previously fiery enthusiasm diminished, and the Revolutionary Alliance split up, reduced once again to merely The Second Escambray Front and Alpha 66.</p>\n                <p>In 1965 <emph render=\"italic\">El Correo</emph>, Alpha 66â€™s bulletin, announced that the new commander in chief would be Dr. Armando Fleites DÃ­az, who was dedicated to continuing the fight and rebuilding military strength. The renewed force initiated new paramilitary campaigns and fundraising for ships and military and radio equipment. Alpha 66 persisted in organizing and executing military operations, sabotages, and creating clandestine cells on the island. Many officers and members were killed during these infiltrations. In 1970 Coronel Vicente MÃ©ndez died in combat, and Aurelio Nazario was captured and executed.</p>\n                <p>After the 1970s, Alpha 66 restructured its underground network. New members were recruited and political activities implemented. The organization established the â€œPlan MÃ¡ximo GÃ³mezâ€ in 1980 to promote internal destabilization in Cuba. As of 2010, Alpha 66 continued to operate from its headquarters in Miami, continuing to advocate for an armed civil uprising in Cuba.</p>\n              </bioghist>\n              <!-- CONTROLLED ACCESS / SUBJECT TERMS -->\n              <!-- END CONTROLLED ACCESS TERMS -->\n              <!-- DIGITAL ARCHIVAL OBJECTS -->\n              <!-- END DIGITAL ARCHIVAL OBJECTS -->\n              <!-- ADMINISTRATIVE INFORMATION -->\n              <descgrp>\n                <head>Administrative Information</head>\n                <acqinfo encodinganalog=\"541\">\n                  <head>Acquisition Information:</head>\n                  <p>Gift of AndrÃ©s Nazario SargÃ©n, 2004.</p>\n                </acqinfo>\n                <accruals encodinganalog=\"584\">\n                  <head>Accruals:</head>\n                  <p>Materials added by gift of Olga Nazario, 2005.</p>\n                </accruals>\n                <separatedmaterial encodinganalog=\"544 0\">\n                  <head>Separated Materials:</head>\n                  <p>Pamphlets and periodicals were separated from the Records for cataloging. Inquire at the Cuban Heritage Collection Reading Room desk orÂ  to chc@miami.edu for more information. Periodical titles include:</p>\n                  <p>Alpha 66 1981-1982</p>\n                  <p>Alpha 66: BoletÃ­n para Cuba n.d., 1975, 1977</p>\n                  <p>Alpha 66: Cuadernos polÃ­ticos No. 1</p>\n                  <p>Alpha: Organo Oficial de Alpha 66, 1979</p>\n                  <p>Alpha 66: News Bulletin. Juventud de Alpha 66, 1972</p>\n                  <p>Antorcha: Buro Estudiantil de la Alianza Revolucionaria 1963-1964</p>\n                  <p>BoletÃ­n â€œEl Correoâ€</p>\n                  <p>El Combate: DelegaciÃ³n San Juan, Puerto Rico n.d., 1972</p>\n                  <p>El Combatiente: Organo oficial del Alpha 66. DelegaciÃ³n de New York, n.d.</p>\n                  <p>Entrega Semanal: Alianza Revolucionaria. Delegaciones Venezuela, 1963-1964</p>\n                  <p>El Grito de Intransigencia (ComisiÃ³n Unitaria BÃ¡sica de AcciÃ³n, Alianza Revolucionaria, Alpha 66)</p>\n                  <p>El Mensaje: Organo Oficial de Alpha 66 para Cuba, 1979</p>\n                  <p>News from Cuba: Alianza Revolucionaria, n.d., 1963-1964</p>\n                  <p>Organo Oficial de las delegaciones del Norte del Alpha 66</p>\n                  <p>Patrocinadores de la Libertad Alpha 66 n.d.</p>\n                  <p>Resurgir/ DelegaciÃ³n Santa Clara, Ca. , 1977- 1978Â  Â  Â Â </p>\n                  <p>Retaguardia: SecciÃ³n Femenina, Alianza Revolucionaria, 1964</p>\n                </separatedmaterial>\n                <userestrict encodinganalog=\"540\">\n                  <head>Conditions Governing Use:</head>\n                  <p>Requests to publish or display materials from this collection require written permission from the rights owner. Please, contact chc@miami.edu for more information.</p>\n                </userestrict>\n                <accessrestrict encodinganalog=\"506\">\n                  <head>Conditions Governing Access:</head>\n                  <p>This collection is open for research.Â  Access to Boxes 19 and 20 is restricted until 2038.</p>\n                </accessrestrict>\n                <prefercite encodinganalog=\"524\">\n                  <head>Preferred Citation:</head>\n                  <p>Alpha 66 Records, Cuban Heritage Collection, University of Miami Libraries, Coral Gables, Florida</p>\n                </prefercite>\n              </descgrp>\n              <arrangement encodinganalog=\"351\">\n                <head>Arrangement of Materials:</head>\n                <p>The Alpha 66 Records are organized into five series.Â  Please see the \"Detailed Description\" and \"Box and Folder Listing\" sections for more information.</p>\n              </arrangement>\n              <scopecontent>\n                <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                <p>The Alpha 66 Records document the political, propaganda, paramilitary, and administrative activities of the organization as collected by AndrÃ©s Nazario SargÃ©n, one of it\'s founders and longtime leaders.Â  The Records include correspondence, circular letters, financial records, clippings, maps, photographs, press releases, proclamations, programs, propaganda, and reports.</p>\n              </scopecontent>\n              <!-- END ADMINISTRATIVE INFORMATION -->\n              <!-- END COLLECTION LEVEL METADATA -->\n              <!-- BEGIN SUBORDINATE COMPONENTS -->\n              <dsc type=\"combined\">\n                <head>Detailed List of Contents</head>\n                <c01 level=\"series\">\n                  <did>\n                    <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id10670</unitid>\n                    <unittitle>Correspondence</unittitle>\n                    <unitdate>n.d., 1958-1995</unitdate>\n                    <physdesc>\n                      <extent label=\"Extent\">13 boxes (boxes 1-13 and one oversize folder)				</extent>\n                    </physdesc>\n                  </did>\n                  <scopecontent>\n                    <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                    <p>This series includes correspondence among individuals associated with Alpha 66, including AndrÃ©s Nazario SargÃ©n, and Alianza Revolucionaria (Revolutionary Alliance).  It also includes materials sent to and received from other Cuban exile associations.  Topics include military operations, activities of Alpha 66\'s delegations, and administrative matters.</p>\n                  </scopecontent>\n                </c01>\n                <c01 level=\"series\">\n                  <did>\n                    <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id10671</unitid>\n                    <unittitle>Administrative Files</unittitle>\n                    <unitdate>n.d., 1966-2003</unitdate>\n                    <physdesc>\n                      <extent label=\"Extent\">5 boxes (boxes 14-18)				</extent>\n                    </physdesc>\n                  </did>\n                  <descgrp>\n                    <accessrestrict>\n                      <head>Access Restriction:</head>\n                      <p>Access to Box 15 is restricted until 2045.</p>\n                    </accessrestrict>\n                  </descgrp>\n                  <scopecontent>\n                    <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                    <p>The records in Series 2 document the administrative units of Alpha 66 and include membership forms, conference files, organizational histories, financial records, military affairs records, and reports.</p>\n                  </scopecontent>\n                </c01>\n                <c01 level=\"series\">\n                  <did>\n                    <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id10672</unitid>\n                    <unittitle>Publications and Propaganda Files</unittitle>\n                    <unitdate>n.d., 1960-2000</unitdate>\n                    <physdesc>\n                      <extent label=\"Extent\">10 boxes (boxes 19-28 and two oversize folders)				</extent>\n                    </physdesc>\n                  </did>\n                  <descgrp>\n                    <processinfo>\n                      <head>Separated Materials</head>\n                      <p>Periodicals titles published by Alpha 66, such as <emph render=\"italic\">Alpha: Organo Oficial de Alpha 66</emph> and <emph render=\"italic\">BoletÃ­n â€œEl Correoâ€</emph> can be found in the Cuban Heritage Collection periodicals holdings. Pamphlets published by Alpha 66 are also cataloged separately.</p>\n                    </processinfo>\n                  </descgrp>\n                  <scopecontent>\n                    <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                    <p>The bulk of this series consists of materials documenting the organization\'s activities: military operations, fundraising for military equipment, and conference activities. It includes articles, circular letters for the general public, clippings, proclamations, propaganda, press releases, radio programs, and works by AndrÃ©s Nazario SargÃ©n.</p>\n                  </scopecontent>\n                </c01>\n                <c01 level=\"series\">\n                  <did>\n                    <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id10673</unitid>\n                    <unittitle>Photographs and Sound Recordings</unittitle>\n                    <unitdate>n.d., 1994</unitdate>\n                    <physdesc>\n                      <extent label=\"Extent\">1 box (box 29)				</extent>\n                    </physdesc>\n                  </did>\n                  <descgrp>\n                    <accessrestrict>\n                      <head>Access Restriction</head>\n                      <p>Sound recordings in this series are not in an accessible format.</p>\n                    </accessrestrict>\n                  </descgrp>\n                  <scopecontent>\n                    <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                    <p>Series 4 includes photographs of events and activities, individuals and groups, and military training camps. In this collection are also sound recordings, including the hymn of the organization, words of Vicente MÃ©ndez and songs.</p>\n                  </scopecontent>\n                </c01>\n                <c01 level=\"series\">\n                  <did>\n                    <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id10674</unitid>\n                    <unittitle>Maps and Plans</unittitle>\n                    <unitdate>1963</unitdate>\n                    <physdesc>\n                      <extent label=\"Extent\">1 oversize folder				</extent>\n                    </physdesc>\n                  </did>\n                  <scopecontent>\n                    <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                    <p>This series includes two maps with handwritten notations indicating Alpha 66\'s military operations and sabotage activities in Cuba.</p>\n                  </scopecontent>\n                </c01>\n              </dsc>\n              <!-- END SUBORDINATE COMPONENTS -->\n            </archdesc>\n          </ead>\n        </objectXMLWrap>\n      </resourceRelation>\n    </relations>\n  </cpfDescription>\n</eac-cpf>\n',0,'/Applications/MAMP/htdocs/eac/ead/alpha_66_records.xml','2013-06-27 15:27:26','2013-06-27 11:27:26'),(11,'<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding