ba. Her father, Gonzalo ArÃ³stegui y del Castillo, was a famous Cuban surgeon who also served as Secretary of Education in the 1920s.</p>\n        <p>Natalia ArÃ³stegui was recognized as a beautiful woman who set an outstanding example amongst her peers. Along with MarÃ­a Teresa GarcÃ­a de Giberga, ArÃ³stegui founded the \"Pro Arte Musical\" Society in 1932 to promote the arts and music in Cuba. The Society is still in existence today. ArÃ³stegui worked as the first librarian for the Society and was the dean of music and singing courses, being a performer herself with a melodic and beautiful voice.</p>\n        <p>Natalia married the famous violinist Remo E. Bolognini from Argentina after she lost her first husband. Mr. Bolognini spent most of his life touring the world. ArÃ³stegui served as a vice consul of Cuba in New York for almost thirty years before the Castro regime.</p>\n      </biogHist>\n    </description>\n    <relations>\n      <resourceRelation xlink:arcrole=\"creatorOf\" xlink:href=\"http://proust.library.miami.edu/findingaids/?p=collections/findingaid&amp;id=\" xlink:role=\"archivalRecords\" xlink:type=\"simple\">\n        <relationEntry>Natalia ArÃ³stegui Bolognini Collection 1913-1956</relationEntry>\n        <objectXMLWrap>\n          <ead xmlns=\"urn:isbn:1-931666-22-9\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" audience=\"external\" xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://www.loc.gov/ead/ http://www.loc.gov/ead/ead.xsd\">\n            <eadheader langencoding=\"iso639-2b\" audience=\"external\" countryencoding=\"iso3166-1\" dateencoding=\"iso8601\" repositoryencoding=\"iso15511\" scriptencoding=\"iso15924\" relatedencoding=\"MARC21\">\n              <eadid encodinganalog=\"856$u\" mainagencycode=\"US-FQG\" countrycode=\"US\" identifier=\"ArchonInternalCollectionID:54\">01/CHC0033</eadid>\n              <filedesc>\n                <titlestmt>\n                  <titleproper encodinganalog=\"245\">Guide to the Natalia ArÃ³stegui Bolognini Collecti