of the 1940s decade and through the fifties he was respected as an intellectual, having earned a reputation both for his poetry and for his influential column â€œPanoramaâ€ which appeared regularly at El Diario de la Marina, of which he became editor.</p>\n        <p>His ideological disagreement with the government of Fidel Castro was immediate, and he left the country in 1959 as an exile. His work was obliterated from all records of Cuban literature including university curricula. At his new place of residence, Madrid, he lived in almost total anonymity for years in spite of the admiration of many Spanish authors for his work.</p>\n        <p>In Spain Baquero worked at Instituto de Cultura HispÃ¡nica and Radio Exterior de EspaÃ±a, wrote articles regularly for several publications, primarily Mundo HispÃ¡nico, and taught at the School of Journalism. He published Poemas escritos en EspaÃ±a in 1960, a collection of essays on Latin American authors in 1961, and one of his most highly praised works, Memorial de un testigo, in 1966. In 1984 a collection of his works was compiled and published under the title Magias e invenciones.</p>\n        <p>In 1988 Baquero was nominated for the prestigious â€œPremio PrÃ­ncipe de Asturias de las Letras.â€ A collection of his essays in two volumes, Indios, blancos y negros en el caldero de America, was published in 1991 and AutoantologÃ­a comentada in 1992. He became a finalist to the 1992 â€œPremio Nacional de Literaturaâ€ in poetry for Poemas Invisibles, and was nominated for other important awards such as the â€œReina SofÃ­a.â€ In 1993 the â€œFray Luis de LeÃ³nâ€ Poetry Chair of the University of Salamanca celebrated a week-long conference in honor of his poetic works. Other tributes included the inclusion of two volumes of his work in the â€œObras Maestrasâ€ collection of â€œFundaciÃ³n Central Hispano.â€</p>\n        <p>Not until 1994, however, was his work recognized in his native Cuba, when a conference about his poetry was held at the University of Havana for the first time since he left the country. Baquero died in Madrid on May 15, 1997.</p>\n      </biogHist>\n    </description>\n    <relations>\n      <resourceRelation xlink:arcrole=\"creatorOf\" xlink:href=\"http://proust.library.miami.edu/findingaids/?p=collections/findingaid&amp;id=\" xlink:role=\"archivalRecords\" xlink:type=\"simple\">\n        <relationEntry>The GastÃ³n Baquero Papers 1956-1999</relationEntry>\n        <objectXMLWrap>\n          <ead xmlns=\"urn:isbn:1-931666-22-9\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" audience=\"external\" xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://www.loc.gov/ead/ http://www.loc.gov/ead/ead.xsd\">\n            <eadheader langencoding=\"iso639-2b\" audience=\"external\" countryencoding=\"iso3166-1\" dateencoding=\"iso8601\" repositoryencoding=\"iso15511\" scriptencoding=\"iso15924\" relatedencoding=\"MARC21\">\n              <eadid encodinganalog=\"856$u\" mainagencycode=\"US-FQG\" countrycode=\"US\" identifier=\"ArchonInternalCollectionID:62\">01/CHC5033</eadid>\n              <filedesc>\n                <titlestmt>\n                  <titleproper encodinganalog=\"245\">Guide to the The GastÃ³n Baquero Papers</titleproper>\n                  <titleproper type=\"filing\">Baquero, GastÃ³n Papers</titleproper>\n                  <author encodinganalog=\"245$c\">Finding Aid Authors: Isabel Ezquerra, Esperanza de Varona and Marta MartÃ­nez.</author>\n                </titlestmt>\n                <publicationstmt>\n                  <p>Â© Copyright 2013 University of Miami Cuban Heritage Collection.  All rights reserved.</p>\n                  <address>\n                    <addressline>University of Miami Libraries</addressline>\n                    <addressline>1300 Memorial Drive</addressline>\n                    <addressline>Coral Gables, FL, 33124</addressline>\n                    <addressline>URL: http://library.miami.edu/chc/</addressline>\n                    <addressline>Email: 