h Collection (digital collection)</p>\n                        </daodesc>\n                     </dao>\n                              <!-- END DIGITAL ARCHIVAL OBJECTS -->\n                     <!-- ADMINISTRATIVE INFORMATION -->\n\n                  <descgrp>\n                     <head>Administrative Information</head>\n                              <acqinfo encodinganalog=\"541\">\n                           <head>Acquisition Information:</head>\n                           <p>Gift of Manuel R. Bustamante, 1999-2002</p>\n                        </acqinfo>\n                        <userestrict encodinganalog=\"540\">\n                           <head>Conditions Governing Use:</head>\n                                          <p>Requests to publish or display materials from this collection require written permission from the rights owner. Please, contact chc@miami.edu for more information.</p>\n                              </userestrict>\n                     <accessrestrict encodinganalog=\"506\">\n                        <head>Conditions Governing Access:</head>\n                                          <p>This collection is open for research.</p>\n                           </accessrestrict>\n                              <altformavail encodinganalog=\"530\">\n                     <head>Electronic Format:</head>\n                                             <p>This collection has been digitized.</p>\n                                             <p>http://merrick.library.miami.edu/cubanHeritage/chc5017/</p>\n                              </altformavail>\n                  <prefercite encodinganalog=\"524\">\n                     <head>Preferred Citation:</head>\n                     <p>Manuel R. Bustamante Photograph Collection, Cuban Heritage Collection, University of Miami Libraries, Coral Gables, Florida.</p>\n                     </prefercite>\n                     </descgrp>\n\n                           <arrangement encodinganalog=\"351\">\n                  <head>Arrangement of Materials:</head>\n                                 <p>The Manuel R. Bustamente Photograph Collection is organized into five series.</p>\n                                    <p>Please see the Finding Aid/Inventory section of this guide for more detailed information.</p>\n                        </arrangement>\n            <scopecontent>\n               <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                                 <p>The Manuel R. Bustamente Photograph Collection consists primarily of hundreds of black and white photographs of Cuba from the early 1900s to the 1930s. There are several photographs dating from the 1950s and 1960s, and a few color snapshots from the 1990s. The bulk of photographs are found in Series II and III. Series II: Havana, n.d., 1900s-1999 (bulk dates 1910s-1930s) contains photographs of the city of Havana and includes various aspects of the life, architecture, and culture of that capital city. Series III: Cities and Towns, n.d., 1900s-1990 (bulk dates 1900s-1920s) is arranged in alphabetical order and contains photographs of various towns and cities throughout the island of Cuba. The Manuel R. Bustamante Papers in Series V consist of materials donated by Mr. Bustamante related to his personal works and educational experiences, including photographs and memorabilia of the Universidad Social CatÃ³lica San Juan Bautista de la Salle in Havana (Sub-Series A).</p>\n                        </scopecontent>\n            \n\n\n         <!-- END ADMINISTRATIVE INFORMATION -->\n\n         <!-- END COLLECTION LEVEL METADATA -->\n\n                        <!-- BEGIN SUBORDINATE COMPONENTS -->\n            <dsc type=\"combined\">\n               <head>Detailed List of Contents</head>\n               <c01 level=\"series\">\n   <did>\n      <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id6316</unitid>\n               <unittitle>Subject Files</unittitle>\n                  <unitdate>n.d., 1890s-1990s (bulk dates 1900s-1930s)</unitdate>\n            			<physdesc label=\"Extent\">16 folders (Box 1)			</physdesc>\n   </did>\n      		<arrangement>\n			<head>Arrangement</head>\n			<p>Alphabetical</p>\n		</arrangement>\n   <scopecontent>\n      <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                  <p>The series consists of photographs of Cuba without specific geographic identifiers and organized into different subject categories such as agriculture, ships and boats, animals, citrus industry, and others. There are many landscape photographs of Cuba in this series in folder 8, as well as a portrait of Charles Edward Magoon, provisional governor of the Republic of Cuba, 1906-1909 (folder 15).</p>\n                     </scopecontent>\n            \n</c01>\n   <c01 level=\"series\">\n   <did>\n      <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id6317</unitid>\n               <unittitle>Havana</unittitle>\n                  <unitdate>n.d., 1900s-1999 (bulk dates 1910s-1930s)</unitdate>\n            			<physdesc label=\"Extent\">38 folders (Boxes 1-2)			</physdesc>\n   </did>\n      		<arrangement>\n			<head>Arrangement</head>\n			<p>Alphabetical</p>\n		</arrangement>\n   <scopecontent>\n      <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                  <p>The Havana series features photographs of the capital of Cuba. Series II is organized into subject categories and arranged in alphabetical order. Photographs of the various forts of Havana figure prominently in this series, as do photos of various street scenes.</p>\n                     </scopecontent>\n            \n</c01>\n   <c01 level=\"series\">\n   <did>\n      <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id6318</unitid>\n               <unittitle>Cities and Towns</unittitle>\n                  <unitdate>n.d., 1900s-1990 (bulk dates 1900s-1920s)</unitdate>\n            			<physdesc label=\"Extent\">54 folders (Boxes 2-3)			</physdesc>\n   </did>\n      		<arrangement>\n			<head>Arrangement</head>\n			<p>Alphabetical</p>\n		</arrangement>\n   <scopecontent>\n      <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                  <p>The series features images of various cities and towns throughout Cuba (for photos of Havana, see Series II). Of special interest are photographs of La Gloria, a town established by American settlers post-1898. There are also many photographs of CamagÃ¼ey and its churches as well as Santiago de Cuba.</p>\n                     </scopecontent>\n            \n</c01>\n   <c01 level=\"series\">\n   <did>\n      <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id6319</unitid>\n               <unittitle>Provinces</unittitle>\n                  <unitdate>n.d., 1906-1920s</unitdate>\n            			<physdesc label=\"Extent\">Nine folders (Box 3)			</physdesc>\n   </did>\n      		<arrangement>\n			<head>Arrangement</head>\n			<p>Alphabetical</p>\n		</arrangement>\n   <scopecontent>\n      <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                  <p>In this series are photographs of scenes from the six original Cuban provinces but that are not identified as being of a particular city or town. Images include views of the YumurÃ­ Valley and Bellamar Caves in Matanzas province as well as of the Vento Aquifer in Havana province, which to this day provides about half of Havanaâ€™s potable water.</p>\n                     </scopecontent>\n            \n</c01>\n   <c01 level=\"series\">\n   <did>\n      <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id6320</unitid>\n               <unittitle>Manuel R. Bustamante Papers</unittitle>\n                  <unitdate>n.d., 1929-1999 (bulk dates 1957-1958)</unitdate>\n            			<physdesc label=\"Extent\">13 folders (Box 4)			</physdesc>\n   </did>\n         <scopecontent>\n      <head>Scope and Contents</head>\n                  <p>The Manuel R. Bustamante Papers consist of materials donated by Mr. Bustamante that represent various aspects of his personal life including works and educational experiences. Of special interest are materials related to the Universidad Social CatÃ³lica San Juan Bautista de la Salle in Sub-Series A as well as other materials regarding Catholicism in Cuba.</p>\n                     </scopecontent>\n            <c02 level=\"subseries\">\n   <did>\n      <unitid label=\"ArchonID\" audience=\"internal\">id6321</unitid>\n               <unittitle>Universidad Social CatÃ³lica San Juan Bautista de la Salle</unittitle>\n                  <unitdate>1957-1958, 1999</unitdate>\n               </did>\n         \n</c02>\n   \n</c01>\n   \n            </dsc>\n               <!-- END SUBORDINATE COMPONENTS -->\n   </archdesc>\n</ead>\n\n','/Applications/MAMP/htdocs/eac/ead/bustamante_manuel_r_photograph_collection_18901.xml');
